{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601688/1938011501/0223.xml":{"full_text":"SILVER STAR-HOME\nVIEWED er 7,000\nDwelling in Westerleigh En\nters Third Period of\nExhibition.\nThe first Silver Star Home of the\nyear, located at 4924 Tilden street\nN W., in the Westerleigh section of\nWesley Heights, will enter the third\nweek of its exhibition period tomor\nrow, having attracted 7,000 visitors in\nthe two weeks it has been open to the\npublic.\nA large number of the persons who\nhave thronged the home have been\noutspoken in their praise of the stateli\nness of the Georgian Colonial struct\nure and the charm and beauty of its\nfurnishings. The attractive plan of\nthe house, with the living and dining\nrooms at the rear overlooking the gar\nden, also has received a share of favor\nable comment.\nAntiques in Home.\nThe home was built by W. C. A.\nN. Miller, developers of the Wesley\nHeights-Spnng Valley section, which\nis known as one of the coifntry's out\nstanding residential communities. It\nwas designed by Gordon E. MacNetl,\narchitect, and has been decorated and\nfurnished by Wesley Heights Shops\nand the Van Dyne Antique Galleries.\nA number of pieces of furniture in\nthe house are authentic 18th century\nantiques, importe* from England.\nThere are many features of The\nStar home that appeal to the house\nwife. The well-equipped kitchen is\ncompact and arranged in a fashion to\nsave steps. There are a large num\nber of cabinets, these with glass win\ndows. The kitchen is separated from\nthe dining room by a neat butler\u2019s\npantry, completely equipped. These\n\u2022rooms are at the front of the house,\nwith the entire back portion given\nover to living quarters. Opening from\nthe living room is a huge screened\nporch, w-hich should prove a delight\nful spot to spend hot summer eve\nnings.\nThe first floor is ideally arranged\nfor entertaining, with living and dining\nrooms and library opening into one\nhuge suite.\nMinimum of Waste Space.\nThere is a minimum of waste space\nIn the home. The closets in all bed\nrooms are large. Storage space is\nprovided in the basement, and on the\nsecond and third floors. There are\nsix bedrooms. The basement recrea\ntion room is at ground level and con\ni sequently is an unusually bright and\nliveable place. It has a fireplace.\nDoors throughout the home are equip\nped with the new keyless locks.\nThe Westerleigh home bears the in\ndorsement of the Silver Star Homes\nCommittee, a group of five housing\nexperts, who examined the structure\nthoroughly before approving it for The j\nStar award. This committee is\nheaded by James S. Taylor of the Fed\neral Housing Administration as chair\nman. Other members are Edwin H.\nRosengarten, builder; John Nolen, jr.,\ndirector of planning of the National\nCapital Park and Planning Commis\nsion; Irwin s. Porter, prominent\narchitect, and Frank Luchs, who\nserved in inspection of the house for\nhts father, Morton J. Luchs, president\nof the Washington Real Estate Board.\nThe house will be open to the pub\nlic for two more weeks. It may be\nvisited any day during this period\nbetween the hours of 10 in the morn\ning and 9 in the evening. It may\nbe reached by driving out Massachu\nsetts avenue past the circle at\nNebraska avenue to Fordham road.\nTurn left on Fordham road to Tilden\nstreet, then left again about a half\nbock to the property.\n\nMORE BATHS REQUIRED\n\nEooms Easily Added, and Give\nBetter Prices.\nA large number of families who are\nIn the market today to purcha.se a\nhome require more than one bathroom.\nHouses that have only one such room,\nor one without, modern equipment,\noften can be modernized easily. An\narchitect can usually find space suit\nable for the installation of an addi\ntional bathroom.\nA house with adequate bathrooms\nfor the number of bedrooms it con\ntains will be found to command a\nbetter price than the home with only\none bath.\nVIRGINIA JOINS\nEoanoke Forms Savings Loan\nInstitute Chapter.\nThe first chapter of the American\nSavings Loan Institute to be char\ntered in Virginia was added to the\nS7 active units of this educational i\nsbody in December. In Roanoke two I\nstaff members and executives from\neach of four savings and loan insti\ntutions organized this first branch of\nthe institute in their State. They\nwill go to night school for professional\ntraining in the conduct of their asso\nciations.\nView of Bedroom in First Star Home\n,s one \u00b0f the attractive bedrooms in the first Sih'er Star Home of the year, located at\n4924 Tilden street N.W., iti the Westerleigh section of Wesley Heights. The home, built by W. C.\nA' N' enters its third week of exhibition tomorrow. \u2014star Staff Photo.\nPrices\n_(Continued From First Page.)\ning. But prices have held in a ma\njority of communities, have advanced\nin 36 per cent and declined in only\n10 per cent of the cities. The smaller\nthe city the less it is affected by the\ncurrent recession.\nNotable in the price situation are\ngeographical variations. The North\nwest region shows the highest pro\nportion of cities with a price increase,\n63 per cent of its cities' so reporting,\nthough not a city in the region reports\nactivity increasing. The Southwest\ncomes next, with 4? per cent of its\ncities showing higher prices.\nI neaper Houses a Factor.\nThe house priced under $4,000 has\nbeen a considerable factor in this\nyear\u2019s building. In 60 per cent of\nthe cities it accounted for at least\none-fourth of all houses built. In\n39 per cent of the cities half of all\nthe houses built were in the under\n$4,000 class. In-14 per cent of the\ncities these low-cost houses consti\ntuted three-fourths or more of all\ndwelling construction for the year.\nBut the very large cities have only a\nsmall per cent of this type of home\nconstruction. The proportion does\nnot run beyond half the home build\ning in any city of over 200.000 popu\nlation.\nSales of home sites during the year\n1937 averaged about one and a half lots\nto each new home dwelling built, the\nreports indicate. Rate of sale in the\nlast six months of the year, how\never. was only about one-third of that\nprevailing in the first six months. In\n161 cities having a combined popula\ntion of 10.544.231 the total number\nof detached homes built was reported\nas 22.948, and the total number of\nvacant lots sold was estimated as\n33.970. If the same proportions were\nto hold for the total urban popula\ntion of the country they would mean\nthat detached dwellings built in the\nentire country in 1937 totaled ap\nproximately 137,910. They would in\ndicate that the number of home sites\npurchased totaled approximately 206.\n684. In making such a projection,\nhowever, it should be remembered that\ncities having an active real estate\nboard are in general probably those\nhaving the mast active real estate\nmarket. If a 10 per cent deduction\nis made for this factor it means a na\ntional total of 124.000 detached homes\nbuilt and a home site sale of more\nthan 186.000 lots.\nThe figures on sale of residential\nlots compiled by the association this\nyear are the first such national data\never gathered.\nSmall Down Payments.\nA 10 per cent payment is by far the\ncommonest amount now available in\npurchase of a home. Down payment\nthat the average home buyer today is\nable to muster is less than 20 per cent\nof the purchase price in 63 per cent\nof all cities reporting. The average\nbuyer is able to pay no more than 10\nper cent of the purchase price in 55\nper cent of the cities. He can pay as\nmuch as 15 per cent on an average in\nan additional 8 per cent of the com\nmunities. At one extreme, represent\ned by 12 per cent of the cities, down\npayments of over 20 per cent of the\npurchase price are commonly possible.\nAt the other extreme, in exactly as\nmany cities, the average buyer can\nnot now muster as much as 10 per\ncent. _\nThe South Central States are the\nregion in which the average down pay\nment available runs most commonly\nto an amount no greater than 10 per\ncent. Almost three-fourths of its cities\n(73 per cent) show such a condition.\nIn the Great Lakes region and the\nNorth Central region only 62 per cent\nof the cities so report. In the South\neast region 52 per cent of the cities,\nin New England 53 per cent make this\ni report.\nIn the Central Atlantic region such\nreport comes from pnly 44 per cent of\nthe cities; in the Northwest region\nfrom only 38 per cent, and in the\nSouthwest region from only 42 per cent\nof the cities.\nAnalyzed according to population\ngroups, cities of over 500.000 popula\ntion are found to have the best sit\nuation as to amount of down pay\nment the average home buyer can\nmake. They report that seven out\nof every 10 buyers are able to make\npayments of 20 per cent of the pur\nchase price or over, while three out\nof every 10 ran pay down only 10\nj Per cent of the purchase price.\nLark of Confidence a Factor.\nLark of confidence in the future is\nthe .principal present deterrent to\nhome building, local real estate boards\nreport. High costs of building, in\ncluding both materials and labor, is\nthe second most important factor.\nLack of operative home builders hav\ning adequate capital bulks next to\nthese. Reduced buying power is a\nfactor, but it is not so heavy an ele\nment by any means as sheer uncer\ntainty of the general business future.\nHigh financing costs and tax fears\nare contributory.\nWhile lack of confidence in the fu\nture was placed as No. 1 obstacle by\nthe greatest number of cities report\ning, high material costs were by far\nthe most frequently mentioned as an\nimportant deterrent. Eighty-seven\nper cent of all cities reporting cited\nmaterial costs; 77 per cent listed the\nuncertainty of the general business\noutlook; 79 per cent listed high labor\ncosts, with' which they coupled the\nelement of uncertainty in regard to\nlabor. Scarcity of operative builders\nwith adequate capital was cited by\n5*. per cent of the cities. Lack of\n\nbuying power appears as a factor in\nonly 57 per cent of the cities. Coat\nof available land is recognized as a\nfactor by 22 per cent of cities, tends\nto be given by them seventh or eighth\nplace on the list.\nTax fears are cited by more than\nhalf the cities, are ranked No. 1 deter\nrent by some, and among the top four\nretarding elements by 44 per cent of\nall cities reporting.\nFindings as to rents, oversupply or\nshortage of buildings, mortgage money\nsupply, interest rate charges, are to\ncome in a later release.\nCONTRACTORS RE-ELECT\nAll officers of the District Chapter\nof Associated General Contractor* of\nAmerica were re-elected when the or\nganization held its annual meeting at\nthe Continental Hotel Tuesday night.\nThe officers are Charles H Tomp\nkins, president; Walter B. Avery, first\nvice president; Earl S. Haislip, second\nvice president, and Prank J. Sheehan,\nexecutive secretary. The four men\nwere also re-elected as officers of the\nMaster Builders' Association. j\nHyattsville, (mTHI\nBeautiful home on fine residential\nstreet convenient everythin*. Frame,\nslate roof. K rooms. Doored attic\nwith servant* room, two baths,\noil burner. I.ar*e landscaped\ngrounds, abundant shade. Two car\ngarage. A nice home or good in\nvestment as two apartment propo\nsition. Might consider small water\nfront farm in part payment.\n_Owner. Greenweed 1H9I-J\nChevy Chase Hills\nA New Connecticut Avenue Development\n$9,850\nYou cannot expect a man who can afford $10,000\nfor his home to pay $15,000. To this end we have\ndesigned Chevy Chase Hills to give a real home to\nthe cultured man of moderate means. A fine com\nmunity with harmony and balance\u2014present in bojh\nthe environment and the architecture. Come out\ntoday and study the architecture\u2014the materials\u2014\nthe selection of equipment\u2014the Surroundings\u2014the\nlittle details that make not only for individuality\nbut for personality and character.\nDrive out Conn. Ave. past East-West Highway to\nproperty one block north of Chevy Chase Lake. t\nThomasJ.\" riGmhot\nINCORPORATED 1\nSUITABLE FOR PROFESSIONAL MAN\nNew Stone Corner\u2014Roberts Built\n9321 1st St. N.W.\u2014Corner Concord Ave.\nA lovely new home containing 4 private bedrooms. 2 baths. 2 stone fire\nplaces. finished 3rd floor, finished basement and many other modern\nfeatures.\nOpen Daily I BEITZEUj 1515 K 5,1\nand w.y Dist. 3100\n1\n5719 YORK kANE\nFIRST SHOWING\u2014NOW OPEN FOR INSPECTION\nSet beck m a deep, attractively landscaped lot, tbe CHARM of this lovely\nhome is reflected by tbe NATURAL BEAUTY of this \"Smart Suburban\nCommunity.\"\nDRIVE OUT TODAY. Inspect the 4 beautifully decorated bedrooms \u20143 baths\n\u2014maid's room\u20142-cor garage\u2014complete oil burner unit. Check for \"CON\nSTRUCTION\"\u2014for \"ENVIRONMENT\"\u2014for \"BEAUTY OF DESIGN AND\nAPPOINTMENTS.\" See if you don't agree that here in GREENWICH FOREST\nis the home you want at o price you can't duplicate within $1,000.00.\nOpen Daily 'Til 9 P.M.\nro MACK:\u2014Only minute*\u2019\u2019 *Mv*\nfrom downtown. Out Connecticut or\nWisconsin Ave. to Bethesda Bank.\nLeft on Old Qeoroetown Rd. to Wilson\nLane. Then h blocks to Greenwich\nFurnished by Peerless\u2014Decorated foreit.\nand Draped by Elisabeth Wilcox\nCAFRITZ CONSTRUCTION CO.\nPhone Wisconsin 5204\nDeveloper*\u2014Architect*\u2014Builder*\nW\u00ab will I>v\u00bbi\u00abn. Elnnnee *nb BniM U salt >nr Individ**! R\u00bb\u00ab*ir\u00bb!*ot\u00bb.\nGreatest Effect Is Produced\nfor Less Outlay In\nHome.\nThe bathroom Is more responsive to\nmodernization than any room in the\nhouse, says the Plumbing and Heating\nIndustries Bureau.\nA small amount of time and effort\nand a moderate expenditure will bring\ndistinction and color into a down\nat-the-heels bathroom and transform\nit into the most beautiful room in the\nhouse. It's in the bathroom that the\nhome owner can make the biggest im\nprovement for the least money.\nBothroom modernization does more\nfor the house because usually it is the\nbathroom that is in the greatest need\nof rejuvenation. Furthermore, bath\nroom improvements provide additional\nconveniences and Increase the livabil\nity of a house.\nThen, too, the bathroom is a small\nroom and for this reason the most\namazing changes can be made with\na very modest budget.\nBathtub Price Drops.\nAnd here\u2019s more good news for the\nfamily with an out-moded bathroom:\nBathtubs today are selling at 63 per\ncent of the base price of 1926. In\nother words, it costs less to modernize 1\nyour plumbing today\nThis is a particularly opportune time\nto add to the value of a house by hav\nNew Southern Colonial\nCOUNTRY ESTATE\n1% Acre*\u2014LARGE TREES\non commanding wooded\nknoll high above Bradley Boule\nvard in the heart of beautiful\nBradley Hills Orove a 350-acre,\nis this stately Southern Colonial\nmanor home, with its graceful white\ncolumned portico. Passing through\nthe lovely authentic Colonial entry\none enters a spacious reception hall\nwith a winding Colonial stairway\nfrom which through wide archways\nare the drawing room, library and\ndining room. There are six bedrooms,\n3 baths, recreation room, maids\nroom and bath, first-floor lavatory,\ntwo-car garage and large porches.\nThe heat is Chrysler's air condi\ntioned air-temp system, heated by oil.\nGENERAL Q ELECTRIC\nUNIT KITCHEN\nIn this modern kitchen with its\ntiled walls are a General Electric\ngarbage disposal unit, dishwasher,\nrefrigerator, range, steel cabinets\nand sink, and ventilating Ian.\nOpen and Heated Sunday\nand Daily in Afternoon\nj To reach property, drive west on\nBradley Boulevard *2'10 miles\nfrom intersection at Wisconsin\nAvenue.\nR. BATES WARREN\nNAT. 9452 W1S.3159\nlng an additional bathroom or a first\nfloor washroom Installed. Unused\nspaces such as hall ends, large clothes\nclosets, or parts of unnecessarily large\nrooms can be easily and quickly con\nverted into charmingly modem bath\nrooms or powder rooms.\nA wide variety of plumbing fixtures\nin matched sets, handsome chormium\nplated faucets, fittings and showers,\nand a wide selection of colorful wall\nand floor materials are available for\nbathroom modernization.\nExpert Advice Recommended.\nBefore making any extensive plans\nfor the alteration of a bathroom, it\nis well to consult an experienced\nplumbing contractor In order to get\nhis advice on the type of fixtures\nbest suited to the rooms.\nAmong the many Interesting new\nfixtures and accessories available to\nday are bathtubs with seats, tele\nscopic shower curtain rods, one-piece\nclosets, full-length shadowless illumi\nnation for mirrors, water-saving\nshower heads and positive quick-act\ning drain controls.\nParticularly in lavatories, a wide\nchoice is available. There are lava\ntories with a shelf back and others with\na room-saving cabinet underneath.\nThe cabinet under a wash basin puis\nto practical use about 6 cubic feet of\nspace that was formerly wasted.\nIn modernizing a bathroom as well\nas In new construction. It pays to buy\ngood fixtures and to have them equip\nped with well-made faucets and valves.\nQuality materials and correct Instal\nlation under the supervision of an ex\nperienced plumbing contractor are\nvery important.\n\nNew Paint for Windows.\nA new paint for factory windows Is\ndesigned to keep out heat and glare\nwithout, interfering unduly with light.\nIt flows easily on smooth glass sur\nfaces.\n4610-4612-4614-4616 Chose Ave., Bethesdci*\u201d^^^^^^\u00ae\nFINER HOMES\nPRICED FOR THE FAMILY OF AVERAGE MEANS\n\u201cCTS=' Just. 15 minutes from downtown Washington lies a new devel\nSAMPLE HOME opment that opens up a wealth of opportunity to the family of\nJft\u00ab a al moderate income. In Westboro you will find a different kind\n4614 Chase Ave. \u00b0f b\u00b0me ali \u00a3uI]y detached, on large lots and in an excep\nneighborhood. Five comfortable rooms and tiled bath\nBETHESDA full basement with laundry trays and lavatory, copper gutters\nFumithed by Hilda Miller \u2122u^\u00abSPrwS flashin?- floored attic, wood-burning fire\np ace Detached garage. Each home a distinctive design\u2014\nplaced well back from the street on lots 60 feet wide Shon\n_ P!n\u00a3 renter with new theatre is within 1 block; 2 blocks from\nTO REACH: Drive out high and grammar schools; 12 block from bus line. Five min\nWisconsin Ave. mo Jutes' driving distance to 7 country clubs and near the new\nblocks past R\u201enk 0f Government Public Health Bureau\nRethesiia to U\u2019F.STRORO x, ro j w\nsign, turn right to homes. Bu,lt b> Claud Livingston. Jr.\nCAREFREE COMFORT WITH MODERN GAS APPLIANCES\nWM. II. SALNDERS COMPANY, INC., DEVELOPERS\nTHE NEWEST\nSILVER STAR HOME OF 1938\n2-STORY AND BASEMENT\nWITH 6 FLOOR LEVELS\n/|\u00a7\u00a7f\u00a3^ DISTINCTIVE NORMANDY DESIGN\n\n4480 DEXTER ROAD\n^PP*\u00ae The original floor plan will be the delight of those who value\nH| the ultimate in unique design. Up or down you'll find\nF only 7 steps between any floor level. Yet every detail of fine\n11| architecture, which would add to its comfort and livability, has\nB been included. Nestled perfectly on a large, wooded lot\nwith a bird s-eye view of Glover Park. A permanent welcome\nB air is provided by the Normandy doorway in tower, topped\nby a weather vane. Large, cheerful living room with open\nB fireplace. 4 spacious bedrooms\u20142 tile baths\u2014shower with\nglass door. Boy's room in top level with built-in bunk and\nEvery home in an individual setting, a pic- book shelves. A gay atmosphere is suggested by the recre\nfure in itself and a definite part in com- ation room in bright colors. These are but a few of the many\n^B pleting the beauty of this community. pleasant surprises that are here to greet you when you inspect\nH r ?\u00b0!uf\u00b0rV n\u00b0tU?' ?Ur' this h\u00b0\u2122 \u00b0f \u21229ic design tomorrow,\nroundings of this fine in-town develop\nmen.. Just 10 minutes from Dupont Circle. OPENED SUNDAY 12 O'CLOCK NOON\nB 'd'Mwinqe'i Bulit\" TO REACH FROM DUPONT CIRCLE:\nDrive out Mass. Ave. to Cathedral Ave. to\nThe yardstick of all fine home construction 44th St. Turn left on 44th St. Drive 3\nblocks to Dexter Road and Silver Star Home.\nH EQUIPPED\nAN ELECTRIC KITCHEN HEALTH HOME\nB *C&fftreumnger'& Sons\nFurnishings by Woodward Lothrop v\nm J. H. Small Sons, Landscaping\nHarvey P. Baxter, Registered Architect 1730 K Street N.W. National 2040","height":"31312","width":"22596"}}
